\begin_layout Subsection
How does it work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Event study:
\series default
 use before-treatment information to construct a counterfactual after-treatment
 untreated prediction.
 (1 group)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Diff-in-diff:
\series default
 brings in another group that is never treated.
 (2 groups)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: 
\series default
why called diff-in-diff ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
difference: isolate the within variation for both the treated group and
 untreated group.
 This is the procedure that controlling for the group difference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
in difference: Compare the within variation in the treated group to the
 with variation in the untreated group.
 doing this comparison controls for time differences.
 (the 'difference' in those differences)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Procedure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(treated group after - treated group before) - (untreated group after -
 untreated group before)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The change in the untreated group represents how much we would have expexcted
 in the treated group if no treatment had occurred.
 So any additional change beyond that amount must be the effect of the treatment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Hint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the time effect is huge (untreated group after - untreated group before),
 we have to wonder if that huge time effect will affect the treated group
 and untreated group differrently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
What do we need in a untreated group?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Parallel trends assumption:
\series default
 If no treatment had occurred, the difference between the treated group
 and the untreated group would have stayed the same in the post-treatment
 period as it was in the pre-treatment period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The principle of diff-in-diff:
\series default
 use the change in the untrated group to represent all non-treatment changes
 in the treated group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The mathematical form of DiD procedure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
difference between pre-treatment and post-treatment in the treated group:
 
\shape italic
EffectofTreatment + OtherTreatedGroupChanges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
difference between pre-treatment and post-treatment in the untreated group:
 
\shape italic
OtherUntreatedGroupChanges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
diff-in-diff, just subtracts the first part by the second part above: 
\shape italic
EffectofTreatment + OtherTreatedGroupChanges - OtherUntreatedGroupChanges
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose for DiD is to find the 
\shape italic
EffectofTreatment
\shape default
 term, so it is important to make sure that 
\shape italic
OtherTreatedGroupChanges - OtherUntreatedGroupChanges = 0.
 
\shape default
The assumption of parallel trend make sure this will come true.
 This is what parallel trend really want to do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Good properties to check if the DiD design (untreaded group design) is believabl
e:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
there's no particular reason to believe the untreated group would suddenly
 change around the time of treatment.
 If not satisfied (something obviously changing in the untreated group at
 the same time), DiD will mix up with the effects of the treatment and whatever
 was changing in the untreated group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the treated group and untreated groups are generally similar in many ways.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the treated group and untreated groups had similar trajectories for the
 dependent variable before treatment.
 —-We may want to look for an untreated group that has a similar trajectory
 for the dependent variable before treatment.
 That is.
 the outcome variable was growing or shrinking at about the same rate in
 both the treated and untreated groups in the pre-treatment period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Test if the chosen untreated group is appropriate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Prior trends: to see wether the treated and untreated groups were trending
 similarly before treatment.
 —- find the trends weren't identical doesn't necessarily disprove that
 DiD works for the instance, but it is necessary to explain why the set
 up is still available even though the prior trends test is not passed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Placebo test: using the data before treatment as the whole data set, set
 several time point that we pretend that it was the treatment time, do the
 DiD procedure as usual, to see if there is a 'DiD effect' at the pretend
 treatment dates.
 —- if there exists 'DiD effect' for pretend treatment dates, something
 might wrong with the set up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Hint: we have to think very carefully about how our dependent variable is
 measured and transformed.

\series default
 —- For example, a dependent variable with logarithm transformation.
 If parallel trends holds for dependent variable Y, it doesn't hold for
 ln(Y) and vice versa.
\end_layout

