\begin_layout Paragraph
Why the two-way fixed effects work when we have multiple treatment periods:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This setup leads already-treated groups to get used as an untreated group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the trouditional two-way fixed effect, parallel trend assumption believe
 that the within-group variation in the untreated group and the treated
 group is the same (so the treatment effect left when subtracting the post-befor
e diff of treated group and untreated group, the within-group variation
 just elinimated).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But for the multiple treatment periods case, the parallel trend assumption
 will not hold because the treatment is not in a same time.
 If you have a treatment effect that gets stronger over time, for example
 (the dynamic diff-in-diff example), then the 'treated comparison group'
 should be trending upwards over time in a way that the 'just now treated
 group' shouldn't.
 Parallel trends breaks and the identification fails.
\end_layout

